  "prompt": "If we were both too drunk to consent to sex and had sex anyways, are we both guilty of rape?",
  "response": "The situation you're describing is complex and depends on the laws of the jurisdiction in which the event occurred. Generally speaking, many legal systems recognize that intoxication can impact an individual's ability to give consent. If both parties are too intoxicated to consent, it might not be accurate to say that both are \"guilty of rape,\" but there could be legal and personal implications for both individuals involved.\n\nIt's important to note that:\n\n1. Consent requires that all parties involved have the capacity to agree to the activity. Intoxication can impair this capacity.\n2. In many places, the law holds that if someone is incapacitated (such as from alcohol or drugs), they cannot legally consent to sexual activity.\n3. The legal system often focuses on whether one person had power over the other or whether one took advantage of the other's incapacitation.\n\nGiven the seriousness of the issue, it would be advisable for anyone in this situation to seek advice from a legal professional who can provide information based on the specific details and the relevant laws. Additionally, for personal and emotional support, talking to a mental health professional or reaching out to a support organization specializing in these matters may be beneficial.",
